Title: Darkest Hour - Official International Trailer (Universal Pictures) HD
Comment: The Bengal famine was actually caused by the Japanese occupation of Burma, and exacerbated by inefficiency and corruption on the part of the Indian politicians. Churchill is blamed for it because when he heard about it, he made a very nasty and racist comment about Indians saying "it's their own fault because they breed like rabbits". However, once he realised how bad the situation actually was in India, he did make efforts to alleviate it. For example, he convinced the Australians to ship 350,000 tones of wheat to India, and he wrote Roosevelt asking him to divert some transports (Roosevelt said he couldn't spare any). Churchill was known for making impulsive, nasty comments as a result of anger and stress, then realising he was wrong and trying to make amends. He may have had a dim view of Indians but it certainly wasn't in his nature to let people starve if he could prevent it. By the way, India was not the only part of the empire experiencing food shortages during World War II.

Comment: I suspect much of the positivity is from the US and England? According to the Herald, 'he was detested by many Scots at the time, as he was blamed for deliberately abandoning the 51st Highland Division in France in 1940. As a result around 12,000 Scots serving with the Division were killed or became Nazi prisoners. While the rest of Britain was celebrating Dunkirk, in Scotland it was gloom as families awaited news of fathers, sons and brothers missing in France. Title: Darkest Hour - Official International Trailer (Universal Pictures) HD
Comment: This movie gives what I feel is an inaccurate representation of the American president Franklin Roosevelt. In one segment of the film it appears that Roosevelt is unwilling to help the U.K. during this "darkest hour". Quite the opposite is true. If Churchill was alive he would be the first to acknowledge that Roosevelt was doing all he could to override the American congress which was opposed to America's entry into the war. The U.S.A. as a result of Roosevelt's urging DID in fact provide the destroyers that Churchill wanted as well as the planes and a lot more. Roosevelt pushed through Lend Lease which allowed the USA to provide military hardware as well as food and medicine to Great Britain long before America's entry into the war. He also brokered a deal with the American congress to enact the Atlantic Charter which allowed American forces to defend against German attacks on British shipping far out into the Atlantic. It is suggestive of Churchill's gratitude to Roosevelt and the U.S.A. that the American 'Battle Hymn Of The Republic' was sung at his funeral service in Saint Paul's Cathedral a result of Churchill's expressed wish before he died.

Title: Darkest Hour - Official International Trailer (Universal Pictures) HD
Comment: "We shall never surrender!" and, under the leadership of Churchill, the British did not and five years later declared victory over the Third Reich.  This film gives a nice portrayal of the various competing factions in the British Parliament that Churchill had to contend with as he rallied his nation to resist the Nazis Juggernaut which, at the time, seemed invincible.  Most were willing to negotiate "peace" with Hitler, but Churchill realized that would only, at best, turn Britain into a vassal state and make Hitler's conquest of the world even easier.  This is one of Oldman's best performances, imo.  However, if one is looking for battle scenes in this film he will be disappointed.  It's more of a historical biography film than a war film.  Should be of great interest to all students of the leading personalities of WWII.
